Furthermore, Europe is experiencing a period of stable natural gas prices
thanks to declining industrial consumption and mild weather. This translates
to lower production costs for urea, further contributing to price stability.
Second Quarter Uptick: A slight seasonal increase in prices is expected in the
second quarter, as planting season approaches and demand for urea
typically picks up. Further pressure on the price will come from a dual supply
squeeze in light of the ongoing Chinese export restrictions, as well as the
Russian fertilizer export quotas that have recently been extended until May
Long-Term Decline: Urea prices are expected to decrease in the long-term
for a couple of main reasons. First, production capacity is likely to expand as
new urea production facilities come online, gradually increasing global
supply and easing market pressure. Second, natural gas prices should
normalize to their pre-2021 levels, further reducing production costs for
urea and contributing to overall price stability or even a downward trend.
